23a4c060-34a5-11eb-b111-fd1354f9c821.description: Paneer Butter Masala Mix Paneer also known as cottage cheese is traditionally used in Indian cuisine which defines sumptuousness in vegetarian feast. A north Indian fare most popular for its buttery onion tomato sauce.  Cooking Time: 15 minutes Serves: 4 Dish category: Main Course  Ingredients required: 1 Cup / 250g paneer, cut into 1” cubes 2 medium / 150g tomato puree Entire packet of Suhana Paneer Butter Masala Mix (50g) ½ Cup / 100 ml milk 3 tbsp / 45g butter 2 tbsp oil 1 Cup / 200ml water For garnishing: 1 tbsp fresh cream  Steps: - Make a paste of Suhana Paneer Butter Masala Mix and milk. - Heat oil in a pan, add tomato puree and cook for 4-5 minutes or till oil oozes out. - Add paste and cook for 1-2 minutes on low flame. - Add water, paneer and butter. Cook for 5-6 minutes on medium flame or till gravy thickens. - Garnish with fresh cream. Serve piping hot with rice or Indian breads such as parathas or naans.  Suhana Tip: - You can use vegetables of your choice like French beans, carrots, green peas, cauliflower to make Vegetable Butter Masala. - After Opening transfer contents into an airtight container. - Store in Cool and Dry place. 93908280-34ad-11eb-8e59-57008709796c.description: Suhana Sambar Masala A perfect Spice blend for the popular South Indian lentils and Vegetable stew A South Indian meal would not be complete without sambar (Pronounced Saambar), a deliciously thick lentil stew overflowing with healthy vegetables like pumpkin, aubergines and drumsticks. Can be eaten with rice as a main course, or as an accompaniment to breakfast dishes like Idli and dosa.  Sambar 1- Soak 100g Toor dal in 1 cup of water for 15 minutes, Strain and pressure cook the dal for 20 minutes with 3 cups of water, 1 diced onion and ½ tsp turmeric powder. Mash it needed. Separately cook 150 brinjal, 150g pumpkin in 1 cup of water till soft. 2- Heat 2 tbsp oil in a wok or saucepan. Add 1 tsp mustard seeds, 3-4 whole byadgi chillies and curry leaves. Stir-fry for 30 seconds. 3- Add cooked and mashed lentils and some water if required. Add 2 ½ tbsp Suhana Sambar Masala. Add cooked vegetables and bring to boil. 4- Add tamarind paste, salt as per taste and simmer for 5 minutes. Serve piping hot sambar with steamed rice or as an accompaniment for Idlis or Dosas  Suhana Tip: Temper with Cumin seeds, asafoetida and curry leaves over the sambar just before serving. For a sweet tinge you can add little jaggery.
